observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that Management:

Require the concerned LGU officers and inventory committee to render at the end of each accounting period all the necessary inventory reports and ledger and property cards following the required format prescribed in COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015 (attached as Annexes A, B, D to E in the Circular);

Require the Municipal Engineer to assess and evaluate the projects recorded in the Road Networks account and provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO (Local Treasurer, in the absence of GSO) a complete and detailed description and cost segregation of the road components indicating specific measurements of the surface type, maintenance cost, initial costs incurred or valuation, date of completion, location and other necessary data;

Require the Municipal Accountant to recognize depreciation on every depreciable road component once all the necessary details are identified; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO (Local Treasurer, in the absence of GSO) to reconcile its Road Network records in order to present an accurate, reliable, complete and accurate valuation of the Road Network account.

We recommended that management:

Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and GSO; 

If necessary, provide additional manpower at the Accounting office to aid in the supply and property management of the LGU; 

Subsequently, require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to: for current purchases onwards - reconcile PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards regularly and conduct physical count, pending completion of one-time cleansing; and

Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification.

We recommended that management:

Install, implement and strictly monitor internal controls over cash collections and deposits to adequately safeguard government funds and records from possible misuse and losses;

Require the Liquidating Officer and Municipal Treasurer to completely submit the duly signed RCDs for September 01, 2022 to November 18, 2022 to properly determine the balances of their accountabilities, otherwise withhold their salaries pursuant to Section 122 of PD No. 1445;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to deposit intact all collections at the end of each day or not later than the next banking day; and

Require the Municipal Treasurer to monitor compliance of all Accountable Officers of the proper filing and preparation of RCDs, proper recording and maintenance of cashbooks and daily remittance of collections.

We recommended that management:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to return the unexpended balance of fund transfers to the source agencies.  For balances with no identified source agencies, remit the funds to the Bureau of Treasury;

Identify details of the P0.363 million fund transfers such source agencies, year of transfer and project status and determine proper disposition of funds with reference to recommendation (a) and;

For accounts which remained non-moving for ten (10) years or more and where settlement could no longer be ascertained, instruct the Municipal Accountant to file a request for authority to write-off, following the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-08 dated August 17, 2023

