We recommended that management:
Withhold the salaries of all accountable officers who are still connected with the LGU until the settlement of their respective cash advances;
Send demand letters and instruct all accountable officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances to liquidate their cash advances within 15 days from receipt or refund the full amount advanced, otherwise, administrative and criminal prosecution may be sought by management against individuals who fail to liquidate or refund the full amount advanced;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to file a request for authority to write-off for accounts deemed dormant and liquidation is futile, following the procedures contained in COA Circular 2023-08 dated August 17, 2023; and
In the case of those who have been separated from service, make representations with the proper prosecuting agencies of the government towards the institution of the necessary proceedings for the recovery of the amount of the cash advance as provided in Section 4.1 of COA Circular No. 86-256.

We recommended that management:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and GSO;
If necessary, provide additional manpower at the Accounting office to aid in the supply and property management of the LGU;
Subsequently, require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to: for current purchases onwards - reconcile PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards regularly and conduct physical count, pending completion of one-time cleansing; and
Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification.

We reiterated the following recommendations:

Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with at least one member each from the Accounting Unit and GSO/Treasury and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Provide additional manpower at the GSO/Treasury to aid in the supply and property management of the LGU;

Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards and reconcile both records regularly;

After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:

Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);

Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there        are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;

Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;

Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and Treasury Unit (in the absence of a separate Supply Unit) and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
Provide additional manpower at the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to aide the Municipal Treasurer in the supply and property management of the LGU;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

Management comment:
The management committed to coordinate with other concerned offices for the creation of the Inventory Committee. The office of the municipal accountant will ask for additional manpower who will maintain the various subsidiary ledgers of all the PPEs. The GSO/Municipal Treasurer is in the process of correcting/completing the property cards with complete details. The accounting office and GSO/Municipal Treasurer are still digging up prior year’s records but find it hard due to lack of manpower.

We recommended the management to
Direct the Municipal Engineer, Municipal Accountant, and the contractor to submit the lacking documents as mentioned in the above tables to the Office of the Auditor in order to complete the post-audit of the said disbursements;
Ensure the completeness of the documentary requirements in form and in content relating to infrastructure projects and programs prior to payment of claims pursuant to COA Circular 2012-001 and Republic Act No. 9184;
Henceforth, direct the Bids and Awards Committee to substantiate its transactions concerning procurement of its goods through small value procurement in accordance with Appendix A of Annex H–Consolidated Guidelines on Alternative Methods of Procurement under 2016 Revised IRR of Republic Act No. 9184 in addition to the usual documentary requirements.

Management comment:
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer committed to comply with the audit recommendations.

